snippet.textDisplay: Tbh a lot of it being unintelligible and unsatisfying isn't the movies fault. That's just it being true to the source material, it's a buzzard musical with basically no plot. The only time the songs actually make sense is when you read them as poetry, the way T.S.Elliot wrote them. Cos then you're not looking for some kind of a plot or overarching theme or characters you give a shit about. You're just reading a bunch of cute, unrelated poems about cats.

snippet.textDisplay: I can't think of a single broadway musical less fit for a movie adaptation than Cats. I personally enjoyed the musical when I saw it, because Cats isn't about the story, it's about the choreography, the set, the lighting, the stylized costumes. It's a spectacle that is only enjoyed to it's full potential on stage. In live theatre, especially musicals, plot is not nearly as much of a focus as it is in cinema, so turning a movie with an intentionally bland plot into a movie, is just a recipe for disappointment

The actual musical of cats does have things unexplained, and is partly unintelligible, but the cats movie takes all of that and makes it not entertaining

None of the cats actually know magic in the musical, though one does perform like a stage magician, none of his tricks are actually magic
